posts.name: Matthew Milunic
posts.cooked: Our robot has recently been experiencing around a 5 second pause in code execution when the code initially boots up. We’ve traced this 5 second gap to the DriverStation.getAlliance() method. This method appears to hang code execution for a few seconds specifically the first time it is called for some reason. Has anyone else noticed this, or is our robot just being quirky?

posts.name: Sam Carlberg
posts.cooked: This is most likely class loading. The JVM only loads classes when they’re needed, so the first call to any class will have to load that class (plus anything it statically requires) the first time it’s used.

posts.name: Matthew Milunic
posts.cooked: That would make sense and would explain quite a bit. The only reason this was causing us issues was because it was happening after the driver station said the robot had robot code, which meant that if you tried enabling it would show up as enabled and allow you to enable, but no code would be running. Is there a place in the code that would run before the robot tells the Driver Station it has robot code? That way we could put a call there to load the class before we can enable avoid accidentally enabling while the robot is unable to execute code.

posts.name: sam liu
posts.cooked: Try calling the method once from the constructer of RobotContainer? Also, if it is a class loading issue, you can check How to Warm Up the JVM | Baeldung .  Altough I don’t know specificially how to do this in FRC environment.

posts.name: Thad House
posts.cooked: I’d actually be very surprised if it’s getAlliance. Instead, I’d actually suspect the line after you’re loading a path or the field from json, which does take long. Is your code posted anywhere, or a code snippet from around that getAlliance call?

posts.name: Matthew Milunic
posts.cooked: To us this seemed unlikely at first as well, but originally we were calling DriverStation.getAlliance() for the first time when our Drive command started in teleop. This caused a ~5 second pause from the time of enabling before the robot would do anything. Just replacing the method call with a boolean lead to no delay at the start of teleop. When we moved it to start calling it during disabled periodic, the 5 second period started happening once the robot “has robot code” and it could be waited through while disabled. Since this was the only change we made we concluded the delay was due to the DriverStation.getAlliance() method call. I will do some tests the next time I have access to the robot to make sure this is still how it behaves just for added verification. Our robot code is public at here . The call is in this file.

posts.name: Thad House
posts.cooked: Looking through there, that call to FieldConstants right afterwards that loads the April tags constants would take a long time to load. Did you remove all the alliance stuff, or just the optional? If you removed all the FieldConstants.isBlue calls, the slow loading stuff would never get loaded.

posts.name: Matthew Milunic
posts.cooked: I will try seeing if that has an impact. Thinking back on how we would’ve called it previously, it used to go through field constants too, so I think FieldConstants taking a long time to load could explain the issues as well. Thank you for taking a look at the code, its very appreciated.

posts.name: Thad House
Matthew Milunic
posts.cooked: Thank you so much! I got around to testing this today, and putting a call to FieldConstants.isBlue() seemed to fix everything!
